-- Migration: Seed Executive Reports
-- Add sample multi-paragraph reports for each executive for the current week

DO $$
DECLARE
  current_week DATE := DATE_TRUNC('week', CURRENT_DATE)::DATE;
  exec_record RECORD;
BEGIN
  -- Loop through all executives and create reports
  FOR exec_record IN SELECT id, name, title FROM executives ORDER BY sort_order LOOP
    INSERT INTO executive_reports (executive_id, week_of, content)
    VALUES (
      exec_record.id,
      current_week,
      CASE exec_record.title
        WHEN 'CEO' THEN
'This week marked significant progress across multiple strategic fronts, and I''m particularly pleased with how the executive team is rallying around our Q1 priorities. We''ve made substantial headway on several key initiatives that will define our trajectory for the year ahead.

Our board preparation is proceeding exceptionally well, with all key stakeholders engaged and materials on track for submission by next Tuesday. I personally reviewed the financial narrative with Jennifer and the strategic positioning with Hank, and we''ve crafted a compelling story that highlights both our achievements and our clear path forward. The board will see concrete evidence of our market momentum, operational excellence, and disciplined capital allocation. I''m confident we''re positioned to secure their support for our expansion plans.

This week I had particularly valuable conversations with two potential strategic partners who could significantly accelerate our enterprise expansion. The first meeting was with TechCorp, a leading infrastructure provider that serves 70% of Fortune 500 companies. Their VP of Partnerships expressed strong interest in embedding our solution into their platform, which could unlock massive distribution for us. The second conversation was with DataScale, whose complementary analytics capabilities could enhance our product offering. Both discussions went beyond exploratory - we''re now in detailed scoping of potential integration points and go-to-market strategies. Follow-up meetings are scheduled for next week with their technical teams to assess feasibility and timeline.

Customer engagement remains a top priority for me, and this week I joined calls with three of our largest enterprise accounts. The conversation with GlobalBank was particularly illuminating - their CIO shared that our platform has reduced their operational overhead by 32% in just six months, which exceeded their business case projections. However, they also highlighted some critical gaps in our enterprise features around advanced permissions and audit logging that are blocking expansion to additional business units. I immediately connected Greg and his product team with their technical stakeholders to prioritize these capabilities. The feedback from FinServe Inc was similarly positive on value delivery but revealed that our onboarding process for complex organizations needs refinement. I''ve asked our CS team to develop a white-glove onboarding track for enterprise deals.

On the talent front, I''m excited about the progress we''re making on several key hires. We''re in final stages with two exceptional VP candidates - one for Enterprise Sales and one for Product Marketing - both of whom would be significant upgrades to our leadership bench. I personally spent time with both candidates this week to ensure cultural fit and alignment on our mission. Additionally, I met with our leadership development consultant to design a more structured approach to developing our next layer of leaders, which is critical as we scale.

Looking at our competitive landscape, I spent time this week analyzing the moves of our two main competitors. One has raised a significant funding round and is clearly preparing for aggressive market expansion, while the other is facing some public challenges with customer retention. This creates both opportunities and urgency for us. I''ve asked the strategy team to war-game different competitive scenarios and ensure we''re positioned to defend our key accounts while capitalizing on any market disruption.

Internally, I''m seeing excellent cross-functional collaboration, but I also identified some process friction that''s slowing us down. The time from "decision made" to "decision executed" is still too long in several areas. I''ve initiated a review of our key processes with an eye toward eliminating unnecessary approvals and empowering teams to move faster. We need to maintain our startup agility even as we add structure.

Key priorities for next week include finalizing and presenting the board materials, closing the partnership discussion with TechCorp (aiming to move to LOI stage), participating in the leadership offsite planning session, and meeting with both VP candidates to extend offers. I also want to spend more time on the product roadmap to ensure we''re making the right bets for H2.'

        WHEN 'CFO' THEN
'Finance closed out the month with exceptionally strong results that exceeded our expectations across multiple dimensions. Revenue came in at $2.87M, which is 3% above our forecast of $2.79M. This outperformance was primarily driven by better-than-expected expansion revenue from existing customers, which totaled $340K versus our forecast of $280K. This is a particularly encouraging signal as it demonstrates the stickiness of our product and our ability to grow within accounts. New bookings also performed well at $520K, just slightly above forecast, with a healthy mix between mid-market and enterprise deals.

Our cash position remains exceptionally strong at $12.4M as of month end, providing us with approximately 18 months of runway at our current burn rate of $690K per month. This gives us significant strategic flexibility and reduces pressure for near-term fundraising. I''ve been stress-testing various scenarios with the executive team, and even in a conservative growth scenario where we miss our expansion targets, we maintain 14+ months of runway. The board will appreciate this discipline. We completed the annual audit preparation work two weeks ahead of schedule, which is a testament to the finance team''s diligence and the improved rigor of our monthly close process. This early completion gives us buffer time to address any questions that arise and ensures we meet our board reporting timeline with confidence.

This week I invested significant time working with Aaron on enhancing our pipeline analysis and forecasting methodology. Our current approach has been accurate at the aggregate level but has shown variance at the deal level, particularly for larger enterprise opportunities that have longer, more complex sales cycles. We conducted a retrospective analysis of the past two quarters and identified several leading indicators that correlate strongly with close probability, including executive sponsorship, multi-stakeholder engagement, and technical validation completion. We''re implementing a new weighted pipeline reporting system starting next week that incorporates these factors, which should improve our forecast accuracy by 15-20% based on our back-testing. Aaron''s team is building this into Salesforce with automated scoring, and we''ll have real-time visibility.

Collections performance has been a major win this quarter. Our Days Sales Outstanding (DSO) metric improved from 51 days last quarter to 42 days currently, which is a 18% reduction and brings us closer to our target of 40 days. This improvement freed up approximately $280K in working capital that would otherwise be tied up in receivables. The improvement came from three initiatives: implementing automated payment reminders at day 15 and day 25, tightening our credit policies for new customers, and having our CS team proactively engage on upcoming renewals. That said, I''m keeping close watch on a few larger accounts that are approaching their payment terms - one $85K invoice is now at 45 days and another $120K invoice is at 52 days. I''ve personally reached out to both CFOs and have payment commitments, but we''re monitoring daily.

On the expense side, we came in at $3.56M against a budget of $3.69M, representing a favorable variance of $130K. The savings came primarily from delayed headcount additions in engineering (two positions that will now start next month) and lower-than-expected cloud infrastructure costs due to the optimization work Brian''s team completed. Marketing spend was slightly higher than planned due to an opportunistic conference sponsorship that Kevin recommended, which I approved given the ROI potential. Overall, our gross margin remained strong at 82%, and our net burn was $690K, which is within our planned corridor.

I''ve also been working closely with our legal counsel on updating our SaaS metrics definitions to align with industry best practices. We want to ensure our ARR calculations, churn metrics, and retention rates are calculated consistently and conservatively. This is important for board credibility and will be essential when we eventually enter fundraising discussions. We discovered a few minor inconsistencies in how we were calculating logo retention versus dollar retention, which we''ve now corrected. The impact was minimal (less than 1%) but getting this right now prevents issues later.

Looking ahead to next week, my priorities include completing the board financial package, presenting the new pipeline forecasting methodology to the executive team, conducting the Q1 budget review with all department heads, and meeting with two banking partners about expanding our credit facility. We don''t need additional capital now, but establishing these relationships while we''re in a position of strength is good practice.'

        WHEN 'CMO' THEN
'Marketing delivered exceptional results this week with our pipeline generation significantly exceeding targets. MQL volume came in at 187 leads, representing a 22% increase compared to last week''s 153 leads and a 34% increase versus our weekly target of 140. This surge was primarily driven by our new content campaign focused on AI implementation best practices, which is clearly resonating with our target accounts in financial services and healthcare. The campaign has generated 2,400 downloads of our implementation guide in just 10 days, and we''re seeing strong engagement with our follow-up nurture sequences - email open rates are averaging 38% compared to our typical 24%.

The team successfully launched our updated website messaging this week after three months of research, testing, and refinement. The new messaging architecture does a much better job articulating our value proposition for enterprise buyers, addressing their specific pain points around compliance, scalability, and integration complexity. Early engagement metrics are very promising - average time on site has increased from 2:14 to 3:02 (a 35% improvement), bounce rate decreased from 58% to 44%, and demo requests from organic traffic increased by 18%. Particularly encouraging is that demo requests are coming from more senior personas - we''re seeing VP and Director level titles increase from 32% to 47% of inbound requests. The new messaging emphasizes ROI and risk mitigation rather than just features, which appears to be landing better with economic buyers.

Our brand awareness campaign planning reached completion this week, and I''m excited about the comprehensive multi-channel approach we''ve designed. We secured three premier speaking slots at industry conferences in Q2: the Enterprise Tech Summit in April (audience of 2,500+ enterprise IT leaders), the SaaS Growth Conference in May (I''ll be on a panel about scaling go-to-market), and the Financial Services Innovation Forum in June. These represent exactly the venues where our target buyers gather. Additionally, we''ve begun systematic podcast outreach and have already confirmed appearances on two top-tier B2B podcasts with combined listenership of 80K. I''m personally taking the lead on our thought leadership positioning, working with our content team to develop a series of provocative points of view about where our industry is heading.

This week I also conducted a deep dive into our marketing attribution data, and the findings are illuminating. We''ve been undervaluing the contribution of our content marketing efforts because we were using last-touch attribution. When I analyze the full customer journey, content touches are present in 76% of closed-won deals, typically 4-6 weeks before sales engagement. This validates our investment in content and suggests we should double down. I''re presenting a recommendation to the exec team to increase our content budget by 30% to capitalize on this proven channel. I''ve also identified that our paid search campaigns are generating high volume but lower quality - conversion to opportunity rate is only 8% versus 18% for content-sourced leads. We''re reallocating budget accordingly.

On the events front, we''re taking a more strategic approach to conferences and trade shows. Rather than exhibiting at every available event, we''re being selective and focusing on smaller, more targeted roundtable events where we can have deeper conversations with qualified prospects. We hosted our first executive roundtable dinner this week with 12 CIOs from target accounts, and the feedback was overwhelmingly positive. Three of the attendees have requested follow-up meetings with Aaron''s sales team. The cost per qualified conversation is a fraction of what we spend on booth presence at large conferences.

Our marketing automation improvements are also paying dividends. We implemented more sophisticated lead scoring this month that incorporates behavioral signals, firmographic data, and engagement patterns. This has improved the efficiency of our SDR team significantly - their connect rate improved from 12% to 19% because they''re working higher-quality leads. We''re also using predictive analytics to identify accounts showing buying signals, which is feeding our account-based marketing programs.

Next week my priorities include finalizing the Q2 integrated campaign calendar (which I''ll present to the exec team for alignment), completing the full marketing attribution analysis with recommended budget reallocations, meeting with Aaron to refine our MQL qualification criteria and SLA, recording the podcast appearances, and beginning preparation for my speaking session at the Enterprise Tech Summit. I also want to spend time with our creative team on refreshing our demo video, which is now 8 months old and doesn''t reflect our latest product capabilities.'

        WHEN 'CRO' THEN
'The sales organization had an outstanding week with momentum building across the board. We closed two significant enterprise deals totaling $380K in ARR - specifically, a $220K deal with a Fortune 500 financial services company and a $160K deal with a major healthcare system. Both deals are substantially above our average deal size of $85K and represent exactly the kind of strategic, high-value customers we''ve been targeting. What''s particularly encouraging is the sales cycle on both was shorter than our enterprise average - 87 days versus our typical 110 days - suggesting our new enterprise sales playbook is working. Pipeline coverage remains very healthy at 4.2x quota, giving us confidence in our ability to deliver on our aggressive Q1 targets.

I invested significant time this week in hands-on deal coaching with the team, which is something I believe is critical at our stage. We have three major opportunities over $100K each that are in final negotiations and should close before month end. The first is a $185K deal with a manufacturing company where we''re competing against an incumbent solution - I joined the final presentation this week and we positioned our differentiation around workflow automation and integration capabilities. They''ve verbally committed and we''re in contract redline. The second is a $145K opportunity with a retail company that has been in our pipeline for 6 months - they finally got budget approval and we''re now in procurement. The third is a $225K deal that would be our largest close to date - it''s with an insurance company and we have strong executive sponsorship from their CIO who was a reference call from an existing customer. All three deals have full executive sponsorship and active procurement engagement, which historically gives us 85% close probability.

This week I worked closely with Kevin to address some friction in our lead handoff process that was causing delays in initial outreach to marketing-qualified leads. We did a process mapping exercise and identified three specific bottlenecks: unclear lead assignment rules that were causing leads to sit in a queue for 4-6 hours, insufficient context being passed from marketing to sales about the lead''s engagement history, and no automated alerting when high-value leads came in. We''ve implemented solutions for all three issues and are rolling out a new SLA framework starting Monday. SDRs will be required to attempt first contact within 60 minutes for hot leads and 4 hours for warm leads, with automated escalation if SLAs are missed. We''re also implementing a shared Slack channel where marketing will surface high-intent signals in real-time. Early testing suggests this could improve our connect rate by 15-20%.

Our pipeline generation motion is working well. The team created $1.2M in new pipeline this week, which puts us at 132% of our weekly target. Notably, 68% of this pipeline came from outbound prospecting by our SDR team, which is up from 52% last quarter. This is important because outbound-sourced deals tend to be larger and higher quality than inbound. I''m seeing our enterprise SDRs really hit their stride with the new multi-threading playbook - they''re engaging an average of 3.2 stakeholders per target account versus 1.8 previously, which is significantly improving our ability to navigate complex buying processes.

On the hiring front, I''m thrilled to report that we extended offers to two senior Account Executives this week and both accepted. These are exactly the profile we''ve been seeking - each has 8+ years of enterprise software sales experience, experience selling into our target verticals, and a track record of exceeding quota. One comes from a competitor and brings valuable competitive intelligence. The other comes from a larger tech company and brings enterprise sales process discipline. Both start in three weeks, which brings us to full headcount for Q1 (10 AEs, 6 SDRs) and positions us well to deliver on our Q2 growth targets. I''m personally owning their onboarding plan to ensure they ramp quickly.

I''ve also been analyzing our win/loss data from last quarter, and some interesting patterns are emerging. Our win rate against competitors is 64%, but it drops to 38% when we''re competing against "build it themselves" or "do nothing." This tells me our competitive positioning is strong but we need to do a better job creating urgency and highlighting the opportunity cost of delay. I''m working with product marketing to develop new ROI calculators and case studies that quantify the cost of inaction. On deals we lose to competitors, the primary cited reason is "better enterprise features" - which is feedback I''ve shared with Greg''s team and they''re addressing in Q2.

Customer expansion is also showing strong momentum. Our customer success team identified $420K in expansion opportunities across our existing base, and we''ve closed $85K of that this week. Expansion is becoming a more predictable growth lever for us, which reduces pressure on new logo acquisition and improves our economics.

Looking ahead to next week, my priorities include closing the three large deals in final stages, conducting the new hire orientation sessions, meeting with our top 10 prospects for relationship building, completing the Q2 territory planning and quota assignment, and presenting our new sales enablement curriculum to the exec team. I also need to spend time with Jennifer on refining our forecasting methodology based on her analytics work.'

        WHEN 'CTO' THEN
'Engineering delivered an exceptionally productive sprint, completing 94% of committed story points, which is above our target of 85% and represents our best execution in six months. The team shipped three major features this sprint: the new advanced analytics dashboard that our enterprise customers have been requesting, a new API rate limiting system that improves platform stability, and a significant performance optimization to our data processing pipeline. We also addressed seven P1 bugs from the customer feedback queue, including a critical issue affecting report generation that was causing timeouts for customers with large data sets. The team''s execution discipline is really showing - we''ve now had four consecutive sprints with >90% completion, which gives us predictability in planning and builds trust with other departments.

Our infrastructure modernization work continues to progress on schedule, and I''m very pleased with how the team is managing this complex migration. The database migration from our current PostgreSQL setup to Aurora is now 70% complete, and we remain on track for the end-of-quarter deadline. This migration is critical for our scale plans - Aurora will give us better performance, automated failover, and significantly improved backup/recovery capabilities. Performance improvements are already visible in our staging environment where we''ve migrated two of our largest schemas - p99 latency for read queries is down 40% (from 250ms to 150ms) and write operations are 25% faster. We''ve also seen CPU utilization decrease by 30%, which will reduce our infrastructure costs. The remaining 30% of the migration includes our most complex tables with the most dependencies, so we''re being extra cautious with testing. I''ve scheduled a dry run of the cutover process for next week to identify any issues before the production migration.

We completed the security review for our new SSO feature this week, which was conducted by our external security firm. They identified one critical finding related to session token management, which my team addressed within 48 hours of receiving the report. The remaining findings were all medium or low severity and are scheduled to be addressed in the next sprint. None of the findings are blockers for our planned release date of March 15th. I''m confident we can ship this feature on schedule, which will unlock several large enterprise deals that Aaron has in pipeline. Beyond SSO, we''re also implementing SOC 2 Type II compliance requirements - we''ve completed 78% of the required controls and are on track for our audit in Q2.

Our technical debt reduction initiative officially launched this sprint, and I''m excited about the long-term benefits this will deliver. After analyzing our codebase and conducting retrospectives with the team, we identified the areas of technical debt that most impact our development velocity. The top three categories are: legacy API endpoints that don''t follow our current standards, insufficient test coverage in critical modules (currently at 62%, targeting 80%), and accumulated complexity in our authentication system that makes it hard to add new features. We''ve allocated 20% of each sprint''s capacity to systematically address these issues. In the first sprint, we refactored our authentication module and increased test coverage from 58% to 71%, which should reduce bugs in that critical system. I''ll be tracking impact on velocity and bug rates over the next 8 weeks - my hypothesis is we''ll see a 15-20% improvement in velocity as we eliminate these friction points.

On the reliability front, we had excellent uptime this week - 99.97% availability with only one brief degradation (8 minutes) caused by a third-party API provider going down. Our incident response was solid - the team detected the issue within 90 seconds via our monitoring, identified the root cause within 4 minutes, and implemented a failover to a backup provider. This is exactly how our incident response should work. We''ve now had 14 consecutive weeks with >99.95% uptime, which is a strong signal of platform maturity. Our error rate remains low at 0.08% of requests, well below our 0.2% threshold.

I''ve also been investing time in our engineering hiring and team development. We extended offers to two senior engineers this week - one backend specialist with experience in distributed systems and one frontend engineer with strong React expertise. Both bring experience from companies at our next stage of scale, which is invaluable. We''re also launching a more structured engineering mentorship program where senior engineers will mentor junior team members on architecture, code quality, and system design. This should help with retention and internal mobility. Our engineering team satisfaction score from our quarterly survey came in at 8.2/10, which is good but I want to get it to 8.5+. The feedback indicated desire for more clarity on technical roadmap and more time for skill development - both things I''m addressing.

Looking ahead, next week priorities include completing the Aurora migration dry run, shipping the SSO feature to beta customers for testing, finalizing our Q2 engineering roadmap in collaboration with Greg, conducting interviews for two open engineering positions, and presenting our technical architecture evolution plan to the board. I also want to spend time with the team on our API scalability planning - we need to be prepared to handle 10x our current load as we land larger enterprise customers.'

        WHEN 'CPO' THEN
'Product had an excellent week delivering against our strategic initiatives. We successfully shipped the new advanced reporting module to beta, which is now live with 5 carefully selected customers representing different use cases. Initial response has been overwhelmingly positive - users are particularly excited about the custom dashboard builder and the ability to schedule automated report distribution. One beta customer, a financial services company, reported that this feature alone will save their team 10 hours per week in manual report generation. We''re collecting detailed feedback through structured interviews and usage analytics. The data shows strong engagement - 4 of the 5 beta customers are using the feature daily, and average session duration is 12 minutes, suggesting they''re doing real work not just exploring. We''ll incorporate their feedback over the next two weeks and plan for general availability release on March 20th.

We finalized our Q2 roadmap during Thursday''s comprehensive planning session with all key stakeholders. This was a valuable exercise that forced us to make hard prioritization decisions and ensure tight alignment across product, engineering, sales, and customer success. Our Q2 roadmap is organized around three strategic pillars. First, enterprise capabilities: we''re building advanced permissions and access controls, SSO/SAML support, audit logging, and API rate limiting - all features required by enterprise buyers. Second, user engagement: we''re investing in improving the core user experience, adding collaboration features, and building workflow automation capabilities. Third, platform reliability: we''re focusing on performance optimization, enhanced monitoring, and infrastructure scalability. Each pillar has clear success metrics and executive ownership. I published the updated roadmap to our customer advisory board this week, and the feedback has been extremely positive - multiple members mentioned they''re excited to see us addressing their top feature requests. Several advisory board members offered to be beta testers for specific features.

Customer research continues to be a cornerstone of how we build product. This week I personally conducted 12 user interviews focusing specifically on workflow automation needs. These conversations were incredibly valuable for understanding not just what features users want, but why they want them and how they would integrate into their daily workflows. Clear patterns are emerging: customers are spending significant time on repetitive tasks that could be automated (data entry, status updates, notifications), they want to connect our platform to their other tools (Slack, email, project management systems), and they need conditional logic and branching in workflows. I''m synthesizing these insights into user stories and acceptance criteria for our automation feature, which will be one of our major Q2 initiatives. The team is excited about this direction - it has potential to significantly increase the value customers get from our platform and improve our stickiness.

I''ve been collaborating closely with Brian on improving our release process and development velocity. Our current bi-weekly release cadence feels too slow - by the time features make it to production, they''re already 2-3 weeks old. Our goal is to move to weekly releases by end of Q2, which will allow us to get feedback faster and iterate more quickly. The technical foundations are largely in place - we have good CI/CD infrastructure, automated testing, and feature flags. The challenges are more process and cultural. This week we mapped our current release process and identified several bottlenecks: excessive manual QA that could be automated, too many approval gates, and unclear release ownership. We''re implementing solutions incrementally - starting next sprint we''re adding more automated integration tests, establishing a release captain rotation, and streamlining our release checklist. I''m confident we can get to weekly releases without sacrificing quality.

Our product metrics continue to trend positively. Weekly active users grew to 8,240, up 6% from last week. Daily active user ratio improved to 42% (from 38% last month), suggesting users are finding more daily value. Feature adoption for our newest features is strong - 68% of customers have tried the new dashboard widgets within first week of release. Customer satisfaction score (measured via in-app surveys) remains high at 4.3/5. However, I''m concerned about a slight uptick in support tickets related to performance for customers with very large data sets - I''ve flagged this with Brian''s team as a priority.

I''m also spending time on competitive intelligence and market positioning. Two competitors announced new features this week that overlap with items on our roadmap, which validates our direction but also creates urgency. One competitor announced an AI-powered insights feature that''s getting a lot of press attention. We have something similar in early development, but I''m pulling it forward in priority. I don''t want to be seen as playing catch-up. I''m also tracking a new entrant in our space that''s taking a very different product approach - more focused on a specific vertical rather than horizontal platform. Worth monitoring as they could disrupt pricing or customer expectations.

Next week my priorities include completing the synthesis of the automation research into detailed product specs, reviewing the SSO feature with Brian''s team before beta release, meeting with three enterprise prospects to understand their evaluation criteria, presenting the Q2 roadmap to the full company, finalizing our product marketing messaging for the advanced reporting launch, and spending time with our customer success team to understand common implementation challenges. I also want to do a deep dive on our product analytics to identify opportunities to improve activation and engagement.'

        WHEN 'CSO' THEN
'The strategy team delivered excellent work this week across multiple strategic initiatives. We completed comprehensive deep dives on two new competitors that have recently entered our space with significant funding. The first competitor, DataPulse, raised a $45M Series B and is targeting mid-market companies with a lower-priced offering. Their product capabilities are currently 12-18 months behind ours in terms of sophistication, but they''re moving fast and have strong investor backing. They''re competing primarily on price and ease of implementation. The second competitor, EnterpriseFlow, is more concerning - they''ve been in stealth mode and just emerged with a product that has some genuinely innovative features around predictive analytics. They have a very strong technical founding team from Google and Microsoft. We need to ensure our roadmap addresses their key differentiators. I''ve synthesized these competitive insights into a threat assessment matrix and competitive positioning recommendations that I''ll present to the exec team this week.

We finalized our partnership strategy framework, which has been a major project for the past six weeks. After analyzing partnerships at companies like Salesforce, Slack, and HubSpot, and conducting interviews with 15 technology partners, we''ve developed a clear three-tier partnership model. Tier 1 partnerships are strategic integrations with large platform companies (like Salesforce or Microsoft) where we build deep technical integrations and co-market. Tier 2 partnerships are complementary solutions (like analytics platforms or data warehouses) where we build certified integrations and share leads. Tier 3 partnerships are technology providers we resell or embed into our offering. Each tier has clear criteria for selection, engagement models, resource commitments, and success metrics. This framework will help us be more strategic and selective about which partnerships to pursue - we''ve had ad hoc partnership discussions but lacked a systematic approach. I''m presenting this framework to the exec team next Tuesday for feedback, and then we''ll begin actively recruiting partners in each tier.

Our OKR refresh process for Q2 progressed well this week. I facilitated productive sessions with each department head to develop their Q2 objectives and key results. The quality of OKRs has significantly improved compared to Q1 - they''re more outcome-focused, have better alignment with company strategy, and include clearer success metrics. All teams now have draft Q2 OKRs ready for review. I''m seeing good cross-functional alignment - for example, the marketing team''s lead generation OKR is directly connected to sales'' pipeline OKR, and product''s enterprise feature OKR aligns with sales'' enterprise revenue target. We have an OKR calibration session scheduled for next Tuesday where we''ll review all OKRs as a leadership team, identify dependencies, and ensure we''re not over-committed. Based on my analysis, we''re currently at about 110% capacity if we attempt everything, so we''ll need to make some prioritization decisions.

The board deck preparation is progressing well - we''re now 80% complete with most sections drafted and reviewed. I''ve been working closely with Jennifer on the financial narrative, ensuring we tell a compelling story about our revenue growth, unit economics improvement, and path to profitability. The numbers are strong, but the narrative structure and framing is critical for board perception. I''m also collaborating with Hank on the strategic positioning section, where we need to articulate our market opportunity, competitive differentiation, and growth strategy. We have a few areas that still need work: the product roadmap section needs to be tightened to focus on enterprise capabilities, and the hiring plan section needs more detail on how we''re building the leadership team. We''re on track for the submission deadline of next Friday, with buffer time built in for a final review by Hank and the exec team.

This week I also completed our annual market sizing and TAM analysis refresh. Our serviceable addressable market has grown to $8.2B (up from $6.4B last year), driven by increased digital transformation spend and expansion into adjacent use cases. We''re currently capturing approximately 0.4% of this market, which demonstrates huge room for growth. The analysis also revealed that our fastest-growing segment (financial services) represents 32% of our revenue but only 18% of the overall market opportunity, suggesting we have significant room to expand in other verticals like healthcare and manufacturing. This data will inform our sales territory planning and marketing allocation for Q2.

I''ve been working on a strategic initiative around international expansion planning. While we''re currently US-focused, several large opportunities in Europe and Asia-Pacific have come inbound. I conducted preliminary research on market opportunity, regulatory requirements, and go-to-market considerations for UK, Germany, and Australia as potential first markets. The UK appears most attractive - similar language, regulatory environment we can navigate, and strong demand for our category. However, international expansion would require significant investment in local presence, data residency, and potentially localization. I''m preparing a business case and recommendation for whether we should pursue international expansion in 2024 or wait until 2025 when we have more scale. This will be a key strategic decision for the board.

Next week priorities include presenting the competitive analysis and partnership framework to the exec team, facilitating the OKR calibration session, finalizing the board deck, meeting with three potential Tier 1 partnership targets, and completing the international expansion business case. I also want to spend time with our customer advisory board members to get their perspective on our strategic direction and roadmap priorities.'

        ELSE
'This week my team focused on execution against our quarterly priorities. We made solid progress on key initiatives and addressed several blockers that had been impacting velocity.

Cross-functional collaboration continues to improve. Participated in multiple planning sessions with other teams to ensure alignment on shared objectives and dependencies.

Looking ahead, next week will focus on accelerating delivery on our highest-priority items while maintaining quality standards. Team capacity is healthy and morale is good.

Key meetings scheduled include the leadership sync, department planning, and several customer-facing commitments.'
      END
    )
    ON CONFLICT (executive_id, week_of) DO UPDATE SET
      content = EXCLUDED.content;
  END LOOP;
END $$;

SELECT 'Executive reports seeded successfully!' as status;
